                    <h3>Design units</h3>
                    <p>
                        Nils talked about units that we can use while designing. It is important to make good use of
                        units to ensure precision
                        and uniformity while making a website.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Figma units:
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>px,</li>
                        <li>%,</li>
                        <li>rem</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p>
                        Units in CSS:
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>px,</li>
                        <li>%,</li>
                        <li>rem,</li>
                        <li>ch,</li>
                        <li>ex,</li>
                        <li>em,</li>
                        <li>vw,</li>
                        <li>vh,</li>
                        <li>vmin,</li>
                        <li>vmax,</li>
                        <li>etc.</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p>
                        Figma mainly uses pixels, percentages, and rem (root em) units for design. It is similar to CSS.
                        Designers can also
                        customize text line-height in Figma, which, like CSS, doesn’t use units.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        CSS uses more unit options than Figma, including:
                    </p>

                    <ul>
                        <li>Pixels (px)</li>
                        <li>Percentages (%)</li>
                        <li>Rem (root em)</li>
                        <li>Ch (character width)</li>
                        <li>Ex (x-height)</li>
                        <li>Em (element's font size)</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p>
                        The last four are relative units that adjust based on context. CSS also has viewport units like:
                    </p>

                    <ul>
                        <li>Vw (viewport width)</li>
                        <li>Vh (viewport height)</li>
                        <li>Vmin (minimum of viewport’s height and width)</li>
                        <li>Vmax (maximum of viewport’s height and width)</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p>
                        These viewport units help create layouts that adjust to different screen sizes.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        CSS also has container units, which are relative to their container element, like:
                    </p>

                    <ul>
                        <li>Qh (1% of container’s height)</li>
                        <li>Qw (1% of container’s width)</li>
                        <li>Qi (1% of container’s inline size)</li>
                        <li>Qb (1% of container’s block size)</li>
                        <li>Qmin (smaller of qi or qb)</li>
                        <li>Qmax (larger of qi or qb)</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p>
                        There are also units like min-content, max-content, and fit-content that adapt to the content
                        they hold.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Understanding these units helps us designers and developers create flexible and responsive
                        designs for different devices
                        and screen sizes.
                    </p>

